## SplitRight Build Plan (AI-Agent Execution + Human QA Gates)

### Assumptions locked from your ER design
1. Core entities: User, Group, GroupMember, Expense, ExpenseSplit, Settlement.
2. A Group has many Expenses.
3. Expense has one payer (User) and many splits (ExpenseSplit).
4. Group membership is many-to-many via GroupMember.
5. Settlement is between two users, scoped to a group.
6. Split correctness rule: sum of expense split shares must equal expense amount.

## Django architecture to implement
1. Project modules:
- accounts
- groups
- expenses
- settlements
- balances (read-only computations)
- common (shared validators, permissions, error format)

2. Recommended stack:
- Django
- Django REST Framework
- MySQL
- JWT auth (or session auth if your instructor prefers)
- Django migrations as source of truth for schema

3. Model definitions (target)
- User: user_id, name, email, password_hash, created_at
- Group: group_id, group_name, created_by, created_at
- GroupMember: user_id, group_id, joined_at, unique(user_id, group_id)
- Expense: expense_id, group_id, paid_by, amount, expense_date, description, created_at
- ExpenseSplit: expense_id, user_id, share_amount, unique(expense_id, user_id)
- Settlement: settlement_id, from_user, to_user, group_id, amount, settlement_date, created_at

4. Required constraints
- email unique
- all amount fields > 0
- share_amount >= 0
- payer must belong to group
- all split users must belong to group
- from_user != to_user for settlements

## API surface (final target)
1. Auth and users
- POST /api/auth/signup
- POST /api/auth/login
- GET /api/users/me

2. Groups and membership
- POST /api/groups
- GET /api/groups
